\begin{abstract}
This essay analyzes the effect of information gathering costs on financial market
efficiency, using data from Prosper.com, America's first Peer-to-Peer Lending Marketplace.
Peer-to-peer lending is the practice of individual and institutional investors
lending money to borrowers over the internet without the assistance of a
traditional financial intermediary. Between 2006 and 2011, Prosper underwent two
major policy changes that guided and then forced investors to lend at higher
interest rates, as well as to reduce their exposure to subprime borrowers.

During the policy regime before either policy intervention (2006-2008), investors set
interest rates by auction, made avoidably bad mistakes, and earned poor returns.
The data from this first regime is inconsistent with three of the predictions of
the Efficient Markets Hypothesis predictions: that (1) risky assets should earn positive expected returns,
(2) riskier assets should earn higher returns than less risky assets, and, most
conclusively, (3) ``prices should fully reflect publicly available information."

Controlling for macroeconomic differences between the time periods of each policy regime
reveals that inconsistencies (1) and (2), which disappeared after Prosper began
guiding investors towards setting higher interest rates, are partly the
consequence of a turbulent macroeconomic period. Inconsistency (3), that strategies
using publicly available information can earn superior risk-adjusted returns,
which holds until Prosper begins directly setting rates, suggests that 
centralized interest rate setting by a market maker may lead to a more efficient market than the
unconstrained interaction of supply and demand, especially when information
gathering costs are high.
\end{abstract}
